  <title>Huang’s Law and the Democratization of NLP</title>
  <dc:creator>synesis </dc:creator>
  <link>https://benjaminhan.net/posts/20200920-huangs-law-gpt3/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=feed</link>
  <description><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://benjaminhan.net/posts/20200920-huangs-law-gpt3/?utm_source=rss&utm_medium=feed">Read on benjaminhan.net &rarr;</a></p>
 





<div class="quarto-figure quarto-figure-center">
<figure class="figure">
<p><img src="https://benjaminhan.net/posts/20200920-huangs-law-gpt3/cover.jpg" class="img-fluid figure-img"></p>
<figcaption>Huang’s Law. Image from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/huangs-law-is-the-new-moores-law-and-explains-why-nvidia-wants-arm-11600488001">WSJ</a>.</figcaption>
</figure>
</div>
<p>Huang’s Law: <a href="https://lnkd.in/gVZjYWg" class="uri">https://lnkd.in/gVZjYWg</a></p>
<p>Today GPT-3 (175b parameters) takes a single V100 355 years, or $4.6m, to train. In 8 years of time we’re looking at a bit over 1 year, or ~$15k to train, on a single GPU.</p>
<p>With massive parallelism this would place models of hundreds of billions of parameters in a very affordable range.</p>
<p>What does this say about NLP? Democratization of NLP?</p>
<p><em>Originally posted on <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/posts/benjaminhan_nlp-activity-6713267126339280896-GRvs">LinkedIn</a>.</em></p>



